- An unbounded pool that dynamically adjusts its size based on demand
- It starts with a small number of threads (often just one) and creates new threads if all existing ones
  are busy when a new task arrives
- If a thread remains idle for a specified time (usually 60 seconds), it is terminated and removed from
  the pool to save resources
- There is no waiting queue. Unlike a FixedThreadPool where tasks queue up and wait for a free thread,
  a CachedThreadPool either finds an idle thread immediately or spawns a brand new one.
  That's why it scales instantly under burst load.